misconceptions.inferred_category_name: Missing input validation / implicit assumption that inputs are always in-range
misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes the input will always be a valid grade between 0 and 100, so they only need to check the lower bounds to decide the letter grade.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: The problem statement defines the grade as 0–100. The program never enforces this constraint, so values outside the intended domain (e.g., 105 or -3) still get mapped to a letter grade (A or F). Correct Java execution will happily follow the if/else chain and produce an output even when the input violates the problem’s specified range; if the assignment expects handling out-of-range values, this solution would be incomplete/incorrect.
misconceptions.error_manifestation: Potential wrong output for out-of-range inputs (e.g., 101 prints 'A'; -1 prints 'F'). For valid inputs 0–100, output is correct.
